ce -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSome 30 years after Glasgow turned towards regeneration, indicators of its built environment, its health, its economic performance and its quality of life remain below UK averages. This interdisciplinary study examines the ongoing transformation of Glasgow as it transitioned from a de-industrial to a post-industrial city during the 20th and 21st centuries. Looking at the diverse issues of urban policy, regeneration and economic and social change, it considers the evolving lived experiences of Glaswegians. Contributors explore the actions required to secure the gains of regeneration and create an economically competitive, socially just and sustainable city, establishing a theory that moves beyond post-industrialism and serves as a model for similar cities globally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh1 aBaruffati, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBynner, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Chik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDocherty, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHastings, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKintrea, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKintrea, Keith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKippen, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https